******
[1] USA (Florida)
Date: Tue 7 Oct 2014
Source: WFLA News Channel 8 [edited]
http://www.wfla.com/story/26727931/floridas-1st-enterovirus-case-is-hillsborough-girl-10


The Florida Department of Health on Tuesday, 7 Oct [2014], announced Florida's 1st confirmed case of an enterovirus D68 (EV-D68) infection in a 10-year-old girl who is recovering in Polk County. This is an update to the Dept. of Health's previous announcement which incorrectly said that the 10-year-old patient is recovering in Hillsborough County. A spokesperson for Tampa General Hospital [TGH] said the patient was transferred from another hospital to TGH about a month ago [September 2014]. The patient was treated at TGH for 6 days and then released. No other details about the patient have been released.

"I don't think there's any reason to be panicked. I think if people use good hand washing, don't rub your eyes, sneeze into your elbows, I think that we can prevent infection," said Dr. Shirley Jankelevich of All Children's Hospital in St. Petersburg. She suspects patients in Florida had mild cases of enterovirus before the 10-year-old, they just weren't reported. "Most of the kids do OK. In fact, the majority of the kids do fine," she said. The strain can start like the common cold or flu with wheezing, high fever, and dehydration. Treatment varies depending on symptoms but includes fluids, rest, and in some cases, oxygen.

The Florida Department of Health advises parents, childcare workers and healthcare professionals to be vigilant for respiratory virus infections such as enterovirus (EV), respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) and influenza (flu). Enterovirus D68 can cause difficulty breathing in infants and young children. Like RSV and the flu, EV-D68 is highly contagious and could spread through droplets in coughs or sneezes or when someone touches a contaminated surface like a countertop or doorknob. Frequent hand washing and non-alcohol surface disinfectants are recommended since alcohol-based hand sanitizers and disinfectants have not been found to be effective against EV-D68.

[Byline: Peter Bernard]

