[Overall only a few cases diagnosed with enterovirus D68 virus infection have experienced severe disease, and most had some had some predisposition. Exceptional was the single case of enterovirus D68 virus infection diagnosed in New Jersey, where a 4-year-old child died in his sleep with no associated respiratory or other abnormalities.

As of Thu 9 Oct 2014, a previously identified enterovirus D68 patient has died, increasing the number of fatalities to 5. Tennessee and Oregon have now joined the list of affected states. The CDC has stated that there are 678 confirmed EV-D68 cases, up 50 from yesterday's 628. There have now been confirmed cases in 46 states, with Tennessee and Oregon as the newest ones. Only Alaska, Hawaii, Nevada, and Arizona still have no confirmed infections, according to the CDC's list (http://www.cdc.gov/non-polio-enterovirus/outbreaks/EV-D68-outbreaks.html).

The role of enterovirus D68 in the 5 fatal outcomes remains unclear as there are few common features. The CDC has indicated that state and local officials have responsibility to determine the cause of death in such cases and to decide what information to release about them. Almost all the cases have been in children, many of whom have asthma or a history of wheezing. The virus, which was previously uncommon in the United States, typically causes only cold-like symptoms, but some children get seriously ill and have difficulty breathing. But it remains unclear whether enterovirus D68 virus plays any role in the mysterious polio-like illness that has struck a number of children in several states, including at least 10 in Colorado. Four of the Colorado children, who had partial paralysis and limb weakness, tested positive for enterovirus D68. - Mod.CP

